1 Q1. CFR of COVID-19

Of primary interest to public is the risk of dying from COVID-19. A commonly used measure is case fatality rate/ratio/risk (CFR), which is defined as \[ \frac{\text{number of deaths from disease}}{\text{number of diagnosed cases of disease}}. \] Apparently CFR is not a fixed constant; it changes with time, location, and other factors. Also CFR is different from the infection fatality rate (IFR), the probability that someone infected with COVID-19 dies from it.

In this exercise, we use logistic regression to study how US county-level CFR changes according to demographic information and some health-, education-, and economy-indicators.

1.1 Data sources

  • 04-04-2020.csv.gz: The data on COVID-19 confirmed cases and deaths on 2020-04-04 is retrieved from the Johns Hopkins COVID-19 data repository. It was downloaded from this link (commit 0174f38). This repository has been archived by the owner on Mar 10, 2023. It is now read-only. You can download data from box: https://ucla.box.com/s/brb3vz4nwoq8pjkcutxncymqw583d39l

  • us-county-health-rankings-2020.csv.gz: The 2020 County Health Ranking Data was released by County Health Rankings. The data was downloaded from the Kaggle Uncover COVID-19 Challenge (version 1). You can download data from box: https://ucla.box.com/s/brb3vz4nwoq8pjkcutxncymqw583d39l

Graphical summarize the COVID-19 confirmed cases and deaths on 2020-04-04 by state.

county_count %>%
  # turn into long format for easy plotting
  pivot_longer(confirmed:recovered, 
               names_to = "case", 
               values_to = "count") %>%
  group_by(province_state) %>%
  ggplot() + 
  geom_col(mapping = aes(x = province_state, y = `count`, fill = `case`)) + 
  # scale_y_log10() + 
  labs(title = "US COVID-19 Situation on 2020-04-04", x = "State") + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))

For stability in estimating CFR, we restrict to counties with \(\ge 5\) confirmed cases.

county_count <- county_count %>%
  filter(confirmed >= 5)

We join the COVID-19 count data and county-level information using FIPS (Federal Information Processing System) as key.

county_data <- county_count %>%
  left_join(county_info, by = "fips") %>%
  print(width = Inf)

We need to (1) manually set the fips for some counties, (2) discard those Unassigned, unassigned or Out of, and (3) try to join with county_info again.

county_data <- county_count %>%
  # manually set FIPS for some counties
  mutate(fips = ifelse(admin2 == "DeKalb" & province_state == "Tennessee", 47041, fips)) %>%
  mutate(fips = ifelse(admin2 == "DeSoto" & province_state == "Florida", 12027, fips)) %>%
  #mutate(fips = ifelse(admin2 == "Dona Ana" & province_state == "New Mexico", 35013, fips)) %>% 
  mutate(fips = ifelse(admin2 == "Dukes and Nantucket" & province_state == "Massachusetts", 25019, fips)) %>% 
  mutate(fips = ifelse(admin2 == "Fillmore" & province_state == "Minnesota", 27045, fips)) %>%  
  #mutate(fips = ifelse(admin2 == "Harris" & province_state == "Texas", 48201, fips)) %>%  
  #mutate(fips = ifelse(admin2 == "Kenai Peninsula" & province_state == "Alaska", 2122, fips)) %>%  
  mutate(fips = ifelse(admin2 == "LaSalle" & province_state == "Illinois", 17099, fips)) %>%
  #mutate(fips = ifelse(admin2 == "LaSalle" & province_state == "Louisiana", 22059, fips)) %>%
  #mutate(fips = ifelse(admin2 == "Lac qui Parle" & province_state == "Minnesota", 27073, fips)) %>%  
  mutate(fips = ifelse(admin2 == "Manassas" & province_state == "Virginia", 51683, fips)) %>%
  #mutate(fips = ifelse(admin2 == "Matanuska-Susitna" & province_state == "Alaska", 2170, fips)) %>%
  mutate(fips = ifelse(admin2 == "McDuffie" & province_state == "Georgia", 13189, fips)) %>%
  #mutate(fips = ifelse(admin2 == "McIntosh" & province_state == "Georgia", 13191, fips)) %>%

  mutate(fips = ifelse(admin2 == "Weber" & province_state == "Utah", 49057, fips)) %>%
  filter(!(is.na(fips) | str_detect(admin2, "Out of") | str_detect(admin2, "Unassigned"))) %>%
  left_join(county_info, by = "fips") %>%
  print(width = Inf)

1.3 Note:

Given that the datasets were collected in the middle of the pandemic, what assumptions of CFR might be violated by defining CFR as deaths/confirmed from this data set?

Because COVID-19 pandemic was still ongoing in 2020, we should realize some critical assumptions for defining CFR are not met using this datasets.

  1. Numbers of confirmed cases do not reflect the number of diagnosed people. This is mainly limited by the availability of testing.

  2. Some confirmed cases may die later.

With acknowledgement of these severe limitations, we continue to use deaths/confirmed as a very rough proxy of CFR.

1.5 Q1.2

What assumptions of logistic regression may be violated by this data set?

Answer: It seems that if we use logistic regression then we will use binomial logistic regression and we assume confirmed is batch size and deaths is the number of success for each county. Binomial distribution arises when we assume that the trials in a batch are independent and share the same âsuccessâ probability. However, in this case, the confirmed cases are not independent across counties. For example, if a county has a high number of confirmed cases, then the neighboring counties are more likely to have a high number of confirmed cases. This violates the assumption of independence.

1.7 Q1.4

Interpret the regression coefficients of 3 significant predictors with p-value <0.01.

Answer: percent_fair_or_poor_health: Every one percent increase in the proportion of people who report fair or poor health decreases the log odds of death among confirmed cases of COVID by 0.05, controlling for all other predictors.

percent_children_in_poverty: Every one percent increase in the proportion of children in poverty increases the log odds of death among confirmed cases of COVID by 0.03, controlling for all other predictors.

percent_severe_housing_problems: Every one percent increase in the proportion of people who report severe housing problems decreases the log odds of death among confirmed cases of COVID by 0.04, controlling for all other predictors.

1.8 Q1.5

Apply analysis of deviance to (1) evaluate the goodness of fit of the model and (2) compare the model to the intercept-only model.

pchisq(covid_model$deviance, covid_model$df.residual, lower = FALSE)
[1] 1.099787e-16

Answer: The p-value is very small, which means that the model does not have an adequate fit.

pchisq(covid_model$null.deviance - covid_model$deviance, 2, lower.tail = FALSE)
[1] 5.669737e-308

Answer: The p-value is less than 0.05 and close to 0, which means that the model is significantly better than the intercept-only model.

1.14 Q1.11

Find the best sub-model using the lasso with cross validation.

Answer: Here I reformat the data to have \(N = \sum_{i=1}^n m_i\) rows, with the binary outcome to represent there are \(N = \sum_{i=1}^n m_i\) Bernoulli trials conducted.

county_long <- data.frame()

for (i in 1:nrow(county_data)) {
  row <- county_data[i, ]
  death_num <- row$deaths
  row <- row[rep(1, row$confirmed), ]
  row$deaths[1:death_num] <- 1
  row$deaths[(death_num + 1):nrow(row)] <- 0
  county_long <- rbind(county_long, row)
}

county_long <- county_long |>
  mutate(state = as.character(state)) |>
  mutate(deaths = as.factor(deaths))
# transform the dataset into a weighted Bernoulli data set

obs_wt = c(rbind(county_data$deaths, county_data$confirmed - county_data$deaths))
county_long = county_data |>
  slice(rep(1:n(), each = 2)) |> # replicate each row twice
  mutate(deaths = rep(c(1, 0), nrow(county_data))) |>
  mutate(obs_wt = obs_wt) |>
  mutate(state = as.character(state)) |>
  mutate(deaths = as.factor(deaths))
library(tidymodels)

set.seed(5)

data_split <- initial_split(
  county_long, 
  strata = "deaths", 
  prop = 0.7)

2 Q2. Odds ratios

Consider a \(2 \times 2\) contingency table from a prospective study in which people who were or were not exposed to some pollutant are followed up and, after several years, categorized according to the presense or absence of a disease. Following table shows the probabilities for each cell. The odds of disease for either exposure group is \(O_i = \pi_i / (1 - \pi_i)\), for \(i = 1,2\), and so the odds ratio is \[ \phi = \frac{O_1}{O_2} = \frac{\pi_1(1 - \pi_2)}{\pi_2 (1 - \pi_1)} \] is a measure of the relative likelihood of disease for the exposed and not exposed groups.

Diseased Not diseased
Exposed \(\pi_1\) \(1 - \pi_1\)
Not exposed \(\pi_2\) \(1 - \pi_2\)

2.1 Q2.1

For the simple logistic model \[ \pi_i = \frac{e^{\beta_i}}{1 + e^{\beta_i}}, \] show that if there is no difference between the exposed and not exposed groups (i.e., \(\beta_1 = \beta_2\)), then \(\phi = 1\).

Answer: If \(\beta_1 = \beta_2\), then \[ \pi_1 = \frac{e^{\beta_{1}}}{1 + e^{\beta_{1}}} = \frac{e^{\beta_{2}}}{1 + e^{\beta_{2}}} = \pi_2. \] So \(O_1 = O_2\) and \(\phi = 1\).

2.2 Q2.2

Consider \(J\) \(2 \times 2\) tables, one for each level \(x_j\) of a factor, such as age group, with \(j=1,\ldots, J\). For the logistic model \[ \pi_{ij} = \frac{e^{\alpha_i + \beta_i x_j}}{1 + e^{\alpha_i + \beta_i x_j}}, \quad i = 1,2, \quad j= 1,\ldots, J. \] Show that \(\log \phi\) is constant over all tables if \(\beta_1 = \beta_2\).

Answer: \[ \pi_{1j} = \frac{e^{\alpha_{1} + \beta_{1} x_j}}{1 + e^{\alpha_{1} + \beta_{1} x_j}}, \quad 1- \pi_{1j} = \frac{1}{1 + e^{\alpha_{1} + \beta_{1} x_j}} \] \[ \pi_{2j} = \frac{e^{\alpha_{2} + \beta_{2} x_j}}{1 + e^{\alpha_{2} + \beta_{2} x_j}}, \quad 1- \pi_{2j} = \frac{1}{1 + e^{\alpha_{2} + \beta_{2} x_j}} \] So \[ \phi = \frac{\pi_{1j}(1 - \pi_{2j})}{\pi_{2j}(1 - \pi_{1j})} = \frac{e^{\alpha_{1} + \beta_{1} x_j}}{e^{\alpha_{2} + \beta_{2} x_j}} = \frac{e^{\alpha_{1}}}{e^{\alpha_{2}}} = e^{\alpha_{1} - \alpha_{2}}. \text{ (since $\beta_1 = \beta_2$)} \] So \(\log \phi = \alpha_{1} - \alpha_{2}\), which is constant over all tables.

3 Q3. ELMR Chapter 4 Excercise 3

The infert dataset presents data from a study of secondary infertility (failure to conceive after at least one previous conception). The factors of interest are induced abortions and spontaneous abortions (e.g., miscarriages). The study matched each case of infertility with two controls who were not infertile, matching on age, education and parity (number of prior pregnancies).

3.1 Q3.1

  1. Construct cross-classified tables by number of spontaneous and induced abortions separately for cases and controls. Comment on the differences between the two tables.
xtabs(~ spontaneous + induced + case, infert)
, , case = 0

           induced
spontaneous  0  1  2
          0 60 33 20
          1 25 11  4
          2 11  1  0

, , case = 1

           induced
spontaneous  0  1  2
          0  7 12  9
          1 22  5  4
          2 18  6  0

Answer: There are more control cases with no spontaneous or induced abortions than the infertile cases. Both case and control groups have no observation with 2 or more spontaneous abortions and 2 or more induced abortions. For control group, there are more people with induced abortions than spontaneous abortions. For case group, there are more people with spontaneous abortions than induced abortions.

3.2 Q3.2

  1. Fit a binary response model with only spontaneous and induced as predictors. Determine the statistical significance of these predictors. Express the effects of the predictors in terms of odds.
lmod1 <- glm(case ~ spontaneous + induced, data = infert, family = binomial)

lmod1 |>
  tbl_regression() |>
  bold_labels() |>
  bold_p(t = 0.05)
Characteristic log(OR)1 95% CI1 p-value
spontaneous 1.2 0.79, 1.6 <0.001
induced 0.42 0.02, 0.83 0.042
1 OR = Odds Ratio, CI = Confidence Interval

Answer: The p-value of spontaneous is \(<0.001\) so it is a significant predictor. Every one unit increase in the number of prior spontaneous abortions increases the odds of being a case by a factor of \(e^{1.2} = 3.32\), controlling for all other predictors.
The p-value of induced is \(0.042<0.05\) so it is also a significant predictor. Every one unit increase in the number of prior induced abortions increases the odds of being a case by a factor of \(e^{0.42} = 1.52\), controlling for all other predictors.

3.6 Q3.6

  1. The spontaneous and induced predictors could be viewed as ordinal due to the grouping in the highest level. Refit the model using ordinal factors rather than numerical variables for these two predictors. Is there evidence that the ordinal representation is necessary?
lmod5 <- clogit(case ~ ordered(spontaneous) + ordered(induced) + 
               strata(stratum), data = infert)

lmod5 |>
  tbl_regression() |>
  bold_labels() |>
  bold_p(t = 0.05)
Characteristic log(OR)1 95% CI1 p-value
ordered(spontaneous)


Â Â Â Â ordered(spontaneous).L 2.8 1.8, 3.8 <0.001
Â Â Â Â ordered(spontaneous).Q -0.06 -0.66, 0.53 0.8
ordered(induced)


Â Â Â Â ordered(induced).L 2.0 0.97, 3.0 <0.001
Â Â Â Â ordered(induced).Q 0.02 -0.56, 0.59 >0.9
1 OR = Odds Ratio, CI = Confidence Interval

Answer: When considering lienar effects, the p-values of ordered(spontaneous) and ordered(induced) are both \(<0.001\). This means that the linear effects of these two predictors are significant. When considering the quadratic effects, the p-values of ordered(spontaneous) and ordered(induced) are \(0.8\) and \(>0.9\), respectively. This means that the quadratic effects of these two predictors are not significant. So the ordinal representation is not necessary because we can check linear effects even if we do not use ordinal factors.
